As sor asthmatic paroxysms, in which the raised and distended lungs almost cause suffocation, there is no reason to think that the lungs are inflated by convulsion ol the pulmonary nerves and thrown into excessive diastole. For granting that the lungs sometimes suffer convulsions‚ the contraction and convulsion of their fibres (if they have any) would involve rather the collapse and contraction of the lungs, as was previously pointed out. Nor is it probable that the lungs are thus inflated by vapours, for flatus contained in the pulmonary veins and arteries cannot inflate them. For even though flatus be introduced by a tube attached to the pulmonary artery the lungs will not swell. And any vapours contained in the vesicles of the lungs could certainly be expelled with ease along with the air. And therefore, I think, we should maintain that this kind of suffocation is caused by the convulsed intercostal muscles and diaphragm‚ for by their convulsion the cbest is kept dilated too long, so that the lungs remain inflated and respiration is interrupted.
